{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_cookie_ver02/data/sn89053307/00517177167/1907113001/0537.xml":{"full_text":"The Fitzgerald Enterprive.\ne BY THE\nFITZGERA:D PUBLISHING CO,\nm MERCEF .o oo e\u00dft and Manager.\nSUBSCRIPTION PRICE $2OO PLR ANNUM.\nW= sre entliled, under the law, to continue all\nsubacriptions untfl full settlewent is made.\n!_ Advertiuing Rates: 10 o;o per inch; 8 cts per line local,\ne Advertisement, .Joh or Subscription will be mocepted\njens smount than 81,00\nSATURDAY, NOV EMBER3O, 1907.\nFitzgerald Gotton Market,\nCorrected/each morning of publlo\ufb02tlo; by H. 6, Powell.\nGood Middling. ...........c... 11\nMidaAlng.... ..coocvesnecinnes 10\u00a7\nLow Midd1ing..............\u00bb\nIR R scinaneesy AW\nRTINS S 3\ne 3\nDublin will issue $50,000 of paving park, and\ngehool bonds.\nPall for Fitagenild or Pull Oste\nMouey is cheaper (3% on call) and other\npings are higher. The business outlook is de\nfdedly improved.\nPull for Fitegerald or Pull Out.\nThe impression that this colony has peculiar\nflaims on one of the New National Soldiers Home\njapreading. It will not be difficult to make our\npims plain to those who are willing to under\npnd.\nThe fact that hundreds of veterans of the\njfand Army of the Republic have voluntarily\njade this their home, in their search for a health\ngl and congenial climate where they may spend\n#ir declining years in comfort, free from the\ns of the northern climate, and where it is\njver as hot as the hot days of every summer in\nnesota and the Middle Western States where\ngreat body of the Grand Army of the Repub\nnow live.\nInthe Fitzgerald colony they have already\nted pleasant surroundings and after more than\nyears trial of the climatic and social conditions\nmounce it an ideal location not only for a Sol\ng 8 Home but for individual homes of Grand\nmy men who may not be able to make a south\nh tour each winter.\nWith reference to the movement.\u2014The Savan\nb Morning News says:\nB\u00a5tFitogerald, it would seem, should be able fo pre\nat a strong claim for a national soldiers\u2019 home.\npbably no communiz of its sizein the Sonth has\nimavy former Union Soldiers among its citizens,\ncolony having been formed largely by men\njom the North and West who had fought o the\nprthern side during the War between the States.\njis to be hoped that Congressman Brantley and\n8 committee of Fitzgerald citizens who are\nprking to secure the home will be rewarded with\nanoaa\nThe Cordele Rambler says:\n41t will be a great advertisement for Fitzgerald\n|4 incidently for all South Georgia if \u2018Fitzgerald\npures Union soldiers home; she ought to get it\nP and if our Congressmen and Senators work\nBively, we believe that they will not fail. Thous\nds of the old soldiers are clamoring for a warmer\nimats and if a home is built in the South at all\nEtzgerald is the logical place because there are\njore Union soldiers in that city than in any other\nputhern community; we certainly expect that\nyery Georfia Congressman will do his duty in\nhis behalf.\u201d\u2019\nPull for Fitzgerald or Pull Out\ni The Water, Light and Bond Commission\nA special meeting of the city council was held\nBE three o\u2019clock Friday afternoon, present the\nByor, Turner, Mosher, Gelders, Hays and Davis.\nThe purpose of the meeting was to provide\nmds with which to pay interest on bonds due\njo. Ist. and as time for paying last half of city\nwas extended to December under the new\nrter the Treasurer reported not sufficient funds\nb 2d to pay this account, and the Water, Light\nBond Commission was called upon for assis\njee, Altho this commission has had charge on\ngwo or three months it has already paid clear\nbfits of 2500.00 into the city treasury besides\nking an unusual amount of water and light ex-\nBions and in answer to this call obligated itsell\njurn another amouut of about Five hundred\ns into the Treasdry today.\n\u2018This is a good showing for the commission\nh is composed of men who have always made\ngess of their own affairs.\nBte of thanks to the commission was about\npd on the motion of alderman Hayes but\nfmar of the commission modestly protest\ns Such a resolution for the reason that\nBlon felt. that it was equally anxious\nsoouneil to further the interests of the\ncomposed of L. O, Tisdel,\nRAILROAD CLAIMS,\nWe have never believed the plan of settling\nclaims for over charges generally practiced by the\nrailroad companics is right.\nSince we have been publishing the Euterprise\nwe tested the theory in the courts. The amount\ninvolved was small. 83 cents, but it cost us about\na hundred dollars and a yeai\u2019s delay before we got\na second and final verdict which demonstrated our\ntheory that when a consignor of freight offers the\nfull and proper amount of freight it is the duty of\nthe railroad company to deliver the goods.\nIn a letter to attorney Jas B. Cummings of\nthe Georgia Railroad last week Chairman McLen\ndon of the Railroad Commission says on the sub-\nJject of claims:\n\u2018\u2018Railroads are quasi-public highways, owned\nand operated by private companies, are created to\nperform and expected to perform a public service\nin the transportation of freights and passengers\nfor reasonable hire. In Georgia there are now\npending something like 5,000 claims for overcharg\nes made by roads in this state, These overcharg\nes arise in a very simple mauner. A. B. receive\na carload of goods or less than a carload andis told\nthat the freight charges are so much. The sum\ndemanded by the agent of the company i 8 in cx\ncess of the tariff rates, and a plain, palpable error\nhas been made. The receiver of the goods know\nthis, the agent of the railroad company acknow\nleges it, and whether it be five, ten or twenty dol\nlars overcharge, the consignee is told that he must\npay the bill and file a claim for his money. No\nmatter how this overcharge may have arisen, the\nreceiver of the goods is compelled to put up money\nto which the carrier has mno rightful claim, and\nthen turn in and, make a fight to recover that\nwhich he feels has been extorted from him.\n\u2018\u201cAs I have said, my information is that there\nare now something like 5,000 claims of this char\nacted pending before the railroads of Georgia\u2014and\nI have good reasons to believe that if in all the in\nstances of overcharge the claims were filed, there\nwould be three times this number at least. This\nis the situation in Georgia.\u201d\nEvery sensible business man whether heis in a\nrailroad oftice or not wil] admit that it is all wrong.\nThe freight tariffs should bg sg simplified that the\nerrors will not be made and if they are that the re\nceiving agent can ascertain the true rate and make\nsettlement for the correct amount.\nBut the most peculiar feature of the case is\nthe fact that most of the errors are overcharges, or\nundercharge is rare. In view of the fact that the\nmen who make the errors own no interest in the\nrailroads it discovers a peculiar trait of human\nnature.\nPull for Fitzgerald or Pull Out,\nAbout this time every year business is a little\ndull. This year the symptom is regarded as re\nsult of the money stringency and is taken more\nseriously by the average business man than would\nordinarily be the case. Dust out your bug house\nand go to work. If the work does not come to you\ngo to it, go after it. There is plenty to do; altho\nthe average laborer, with the improved methods\nand devices of the present time accomplishes more\nin a day than he could have accomplished in a\nweek a hundred years ago, or in a month a thou\nsand years ago, or in a year centuries ago. There\nis more to do. Instead of the caves of ages ago, or\nthe huts of a thousand years ago or the cheap\nhouses of a hundred years ago we live in palaces\nnow. The common laborer of today lives in the\nluxury of the rich of even a century ago., Palace\ncars and palace ships are not the only luxuries but\nfair samples of the worlds, great wealth.\nThere is no turning back; the world has come\nto know the word sumptuous and while a wild set\nof financiers may occasionally \u2018\u2018shake confidence\u2019\nbut it is only the fool who reckons that prosperity\nis at an end.\nGET BUSY AT SOMETHING USEPUL.\nPull for Fitzgerald or Pull Qut.\n24 INCH PISTGLS.\nFrom The Georglan.'\nAlabama has decided, and that upoun a special\ncall of the legislature, which required a larger\nvote than otherwise would have been necessary, to\nprohibit the manufacture and sale of liquor after\nnext year. Birmingham and a number of other\nplaces put the law into effect January 1, 1908.\nThey arca little more radical in Alabama than we\nwere, and are tieing theirstate even alittle tighter\nthan we did on the liquor propesition. Then, too,\nthey have passed a law prohibiting the carrying of\na pistol under 23 inches long. Shades of Socrates?\u2014\nthey will b 2 trying to stop dishoncesty next.\nI\"ull for Fitzgerald or ull Qut.\n1t now turns out that the panie was manufact\nured for political purposes,\u2014to discredit the Rose\nvelt administration and it turned out bad for the\nmanipulators.\nPull for Fitsgerald or Pull Out.\nThe Georgia Military will be completely re\norganized under an order issued by Governor\nSmith this week.\nPull for Fitegerald or Pull Oute\nThe grand jury of Lowdnes county has in\ndicted the steward of the Eagles Club. They\nhave lockers at the club, weexpect to see lots of\nValdosta Savannah boozers in trouble before they\ncome to a full realization that the people of Geor\ngid are \u2018\u2018agiy\u2019\u2019 John Barleycorn.\nConpliuwibdlteqzimudtheNn\ufb01ondeeFoodhw.Gmeo.le.\ufb01leanahhm\nA B\\ sl L e\nBN B SRS S DBN Y 20\ne NNI\n;/,f\u2018. B /egA\\\" R\n\ufb01 (\u2019l st V\u2019\nMY )ey! A 1 9\\\\,\" e. 3 o\nS} l LAL Y R L N\\ o\n'\\\\'&~-4 |2\no x; f\u2019/ B ale\no L\u2018Y\nDrink the old original Arbuckles\u2019 i Q years, exceed the combined sales\nARIOSA Coffee, the blend of lof all the other pac\ufb02ga coffees.\n--ele e i e\nBrazilian coffees, most wholesome\nand stimulating, as well as most\neconomical. Anything dearer\nthan Arbuckles ARIOSA is\nextt:::fant, and no one can sell\nas coffee for the same price.\nPe\ufb01ilZ who drink Arbuckles\u2019\nARIOSA Coffee are not dys\npeptics with fashionable nesves\nAunouncements.\nA AP PNSNT NI NI NI NS NN NI NN NI\nFOR CITY TREASURER.\n1 hereby announce. myself as\ncandidate for the office of City\nTreasurer subject to the voters at\nthe coming city election.\nRespectively\nA. A. HARVEY,\nFOR CITY TREASUSER.\nTo the Voters of the City\nof Fitzgerald\u2014l am a candidate\nfor the office of City Treasurer at\nthe December election, and I\nearnestly solicit the support of\nevery voter in Fitzgerald.\nRespectfully,\nG. P. MINGLEDORFF.\nFOR CITY MARSHAL.\nTo the Voters of the City of Fitz\ngerald, Ga.:\nT am a candidate for City Mar\nshal of Fitzgerald at the coming\nelection and earnestly solicit your\nsupport. Respectfully,\nFrANK HAGER.\nTo the voters of Fitzgerald: 1\nam a candidate for the office of City\nMarshal at the coming election, and\nearnestly solicit your support,\nOct. 31, 1907.\nRespectfully,\nHERMAN SMITH,\nFOR CITY MARSHALL.\n\u2018I desire to announce mysell as a\ncandidate for election as Cit)\nMarshall subject to the choice o.\nthe voters of Fitzgerald and i\nelected I promise a faithful and\npainstaking discharge of the duties\nof the office. 1 will appreeiate\nyour support. Sincerely yours,\nC. E. HARRISON.\nNOTICE OF ELECTION.\nNotice is hereby given that on\nTuesday the 17th day of December\n1907, an election will be held af\nthe City Hall in the City of Fitz\ngerald for the purpose of clecting\nthe following officers for said City,\nto wit: One Mayor, five Aldermen\nat- larze, oune City Marshal, one\nCity Treasurer, one City tax asses\nsor and eight members of the Board\nof Education from the City at\nlarge. The polls for said election\nwill be open at 8 o\u2019clock in the\nforenoon. No ballots will be re\nceived by the managers of said\nelection at the polling place execept\nthe official ballot whieh will be\nfurnished the voter by the election\nmanager after such voter enters\nthe voting place for the purpose of\ncasting his ballot.\nBy order of the City Council\nthis November 6, 1907.\nJ. G. Knapp,\nC. M. Wise, Clerk. Mayor\nPut down a little tile pavement\nin front of your home, it will beau\ntify and improve your property\nand will add to the general ap\npearance of thrift of the city.\nSouthern Granitoid Co.\ntf C. W, Hayes, Manager.\nGet Busy at Something Useful.\nThe National Barber Shop.\nFirst Class in every particular.\nBATHS. Empire Building, Central\navenye. Owen Bros. prop. 44tf,\ns\nwho take vacations in Sanitariums,\non featherweight rations, but the\nhealthy vigorous manhood and\nwomanhood that constitute the\nuseful majority. The first roasted\npackaged coffee sales of Arbuck\nles ARIOSA Coffee for 37\nDo You Eat?\n\u2014\u2014\u2014my O G\nThe Vendome Grocery\ne\ntrictly Cash More\nNrictly Gash More\nw\nRetailers of Everything Good\nTo Eat!\n61bs. Lump Stareh........cocviiinreniions 8 .25\nArmour\u2019s Hams, perllb.........coooevvvieanenn. 15\n10-Ib, Pail Plantine........ccicviieaivnennono 1.15\nCompound Lard, per Ib........oooveenvnneenes J 1\nAll Standard brands canned C0rn.............. 10\u00a2\nTomatoes, 3 CANS,, ccescevroereoscocsasenses 25\u00a2\n18 Ibs. best Graulated Sugar with all 3 orders.. 1.00\nSweet Potatoes 15\u00a2 peck; perbu................ .5d\nIrish Potatoes, per peck.........ovovvveeiennns .30\nGood Roasted Coftee, perllb.........ooovvennn. 123\nNew York State Baldwin Apples, per peck....... .60\nChoice Santa Clara Prunes.......c.oooevneeeess 10\nAvbuckles Th. coorvios v vve i i dans 18\nVan Camp\u2019s Hominy, \u20acan........coovevveeennee .10\nGood Salmon, \u20acam.........c..ciueemneennanenns 10\nGood Mackerel, \u20acan.........oooeveveccncnenen .10\nCape Cod Cranberries, quart. ......c.ooeeeee.ee Ag\nGahibige 18.